Parliament has reconstituted its Committee on Selection replacing ten members in the crucial House team. Those shown door included mostly lawmakers who were last month dewhipped by the respective parties for alleged disloyalty and links to Deputy President William Ruto. They included Beatrice Nkatha (Tharaka-Nithi MP), Khatib Mwashetani (Lunga Lunga), Faith Gitau (Nyandarua MP), John Kiarie (Dagoretti South), William Kipkemoi (Marakwet West), Robert Githinji (Gichugu), John Paul Mwirigi (Igembe South), Tindi Mwale (Butere) and Catherine Wambilianga (Bungoma MP). The changes followed a resolution of House Business Committee chaired by Speaker Justin Muturi on Thursday morning. The lawmakers in the afternoon sitting approved the new list of MPs who are mostly pro-handshake between President Uhuru Kenyatta and opposition leader Raila Odinga to take over the affairs of the committee. They were deputy minority whip Maoka Maore (Igembe North), Jane Wanjiku (Embu MP), Gathoni Wamuchomba (Kiambu MP), Joshua Kutuny (Cherengany), Maina Kamanda (nominated), Shurie Abdi Omar (Balambala), Wachira Kabinga (Mwea), Eseli Simiyu (Tongaren) and Godfrey Osotsi (nominated). Leader of the Majority party as the chairperson chairs the committee which has the Leader of the Minority party and not less than eleven and not more than nineteen members, who are nominated by parliamentary parties and approved by the House The Committee on Selection core function is the nomination of members to serve in Committees save for the membership of the House Business Committee and Committee on Appointments. Traditionally, the Committee on Selection is appointed within ten days on assembly of a new House.